title: For Sale/Trade:  2006 Kawasaki Ninja 650r
postcontent:
Looking to either sell or trade this great little bike. In perfect mechanical condition with a bit over 4k miles on it. I bought it from the first owner, who low sided at 35 on a country road and ripped the fairings off. I got it at a good price with the intention of making it a street fighter. I got new turn signals and a headlight for it thinking I could easily throw them on and wire them in. And then I realized all of my mechanicing experience was on 80's American cars with simple mechanical systems and no electronic tom-foolery. I could probably figure out the wiring harness and all that eventually, but I'd rather spend that time riding. I was given a quote of $400 to give it a tuneup, mount a new rear tire (I have the new rubber just no way to mount it), and wire in the new headlight and turn signals. Honestly though, I feel kind of stupid every time I look at the damn thing and would really prefer to just get rid of it and start over.

Ideally I'd like to trade this. If you have a bike in good running condition that you're looking to upgrade and either have the know how to wire in the electric bits or just want to have someone else do it for you it seems like a win win. You get a great bike at a low cost, and I don't have to feel like a dumbass every time I walk out into the garage. I'm especially interested in older Honda Magna's and Yamaha Seca II's but I'm very open to anything in good running shape. I'd like $1800 for the bike, new parts, and new tire in a straight sale. I have a clean title, although I can't find the actual paper so I'll give you the registration and a Release of Interest. Here are a couple crappy cell phone pics, I'm happy to get more or add additional detail if you're interested.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington 20 gauge Semiauto
location: Garner, NC, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
A lighter, streamlined version, of the Model 11 the Model 48 was the first new shotgun to be introduced by Remington after World War II. The 11-48 differs from the Model 11 in the shape of its machined steel receiver and the use of stamped steel internal parts. The new easily removable aluminum trigger housing was to be featured on its successors, the 1100 and the 11-87. The 48 was also one of the first shotguns to feature a self-adjusting friction ring. The Mohawk '48 variant is one of the last 11-48's produced cleaned up a lot of the shotgun's early problems. 

This is fully function shotgun, it shoots well (my son killed dove last season).  It is an excellent starter gun for kids, ladies, or guys with short length of pull needs.  The stock on these is not terribly short and is the original wood.  Have not refinished, gun nothing done to it at all since it was bought in 1982 from a friend of the family.

title: For Sale:  Para Ordnance AR-15 TTR Tactical Target Rifle
postcontent:
The Para Ordnance TTR (Tactical Target Rifle) was originally designed and built by ZM Weapons as the LR-300.  Para TTR uses a trademarked Delayed Impingement Gas System (DIGS) designed by Allan Zitta to get the shooter back on target faster than any other rifle in its class. The system utilizes a unique modified gas key sporting a nickeled operating rod that runs through the upper receiver and over the barrel to the gas block where it sleeves the chrome-plated gas tube, with the recoil spring over the gas tube on top of the barrel.  No buffer tube or spring in the stock (which reduces overall length by almost 10” when folded)!  Stock and tube are by Yankee Hill machine as are the sights.
The charging handle is beefier and features a channel that redirects any gas heading towards the shooter’s face out to the side. Drawing the charging handle on the TTR is more like drawing a bow’s string than charging a typical AR. That’s because you’re stretching the op rod’s spring system rather than compressing it. Locking the bolt to the rear always means that the charging handle is always pulled back into the receiver.
Releasing the action allows the op rod spring to drive the bolt carrier assembly with such force that it’s hard to imagine a situation where it would be necessary to use the forward assist to lock the bolt into the chamber. Combine the fact that a scarce amount of carbon fouling ever enters the chamber with the benefit of the op rod spring translates into enhanced reliability.
Field stripping the upper receiver on the TTR starts with the top rail and is different than a typical AR. Depress a spring-loaded plunger and slide the top rail on the handguard forward to remove it. Draw the action spring back and remove the retaining clip, easing the spring forward. With the upper broken down, shotgun style or completely removed from the lower receiver, remove the charging handle by pulling it rearward from the receiver. The charging handle also brings the bolt carrier assembly and operating rod with it. From this point, disassembly, care and maintenance are identical to a typical AR rifle.
I paid $2400.00 plus tax.  About 200 rounds (+/-) put through this rifle.  Condition is excellent.  Asking $1800 or make an offer!  (Come with a case)

title: For Sale:  FS: New Stag Model 2 w/Plus Package and a WHOLE LOT MORE!!!
location: Columbus and surrounding area, Columbus, Ohio
postcontent:
This is not just another inflated AR deal.  This is going for well below what I have in it at non-inflated pricing.  

This is a Stag Model 2 with Stag's plus package.  The plus package puts the Model 2 at a full Mil-spec tier from tube to tube.  Along with A LOT of brand new upgraded parts.  

A little about Stag (it's been done to death, but for those who don't know).  Stag Arms is sister company, or retail face, of Continental Machine and Tool (CMT).  If you own an AR from Colt, Bravo Company, or damn near any other company that makes or assembles AR's then you probably own a part from CMT.  CMT has made bolts for Colt, they make upper assembly's for Bravo Company (as well as lowers and barrels), and have been supplying just about everyone out there with AR parts for years.  The owner of CMT is the father or the owner of Stag.  CMT makes everything in a Stag rifle.

All that being said, a base model Stag is not a Colt, and is not a Bravo rifle.  However, a Stag rifle with their optional "Plus Package" is absolutely comparable.  Their Plus Package is comprised of the same mil-spec components, and held to the same MPI/HPI inspections as the parts CMT delivers to the top tier guys.  

Why the price difference...$1100 for a Stag with the "Plus Package" and $1900 for a BCM if they're the same rifle you ask?  Stag/CMT makes everything on their rifles, whereas BCM and others have to contract and assemble the contracted parts bought elsewhere.  Quite a bit more expensive.  

Ok, enough of the sales pitch.  This rifle sells itself.  It is absolutely on par with any top tier direct gas M4/AR I've ever owned.  Beats the crap out of any Colt I had in the service, that's a fact!  There is ZERO play between the upper and lower.  No need for any added wedge crap that will wear other parts faster...just tight tolerance.  All parts are the ever UN-importantly important mil-spec (barrel is 4150 CMV chrome lined, chrome lined BCG and chrome lined properly staked gas key, shot peened Carpenter-158 MPI/HPI bolt w/tool steel extractor and black (not blue) extractor spring, mil-spec buffer tube, and mil-spec single stage trigger group, and M4 feed ramps, 556).  Also, this riffle is right around 30 days old.  I put 60 rounds out of 100 through it to make sure it was good to go and dial in an EOTech 552 (already sold, don't ask :)), you get the remaining 40 so you can play with it without burning you own.  All the upgraded parts were bought specifically for this rifle brand new and I'm selling everything with it.  There are ZERO issues with this rifle, trigger is crisp and creep free...it is perfect.  I'm selling it to fund other interests at the moment.  All prices are what I paid (minus tax and shipping when applicable), they are just for reference.  As I said, I don't expect to sell it for what I have in it.

Upgraded Parts Included (but not installed):

Burris 1" P.E.P.R. Return-to-Zero One Piece Scope Mount ($110)

LMT labeled SOPMOD Stock ($0, don't get excited...it's nice, but 100% fake.  Some A-hole on Armslist pawned this off on me because I didn't look at it close enough until after the deal was done...now he doesn't answer his phone because, as I found out, I'm not the only one...effing coward!!!) 
All the original Stag paperwork, bolt lock, drink koozie, etc. that came with it
I'll also include two 30rd mags that I bought for $20ea at Buckeye outdoors.

Everything I am offering is 100% legit and authentic (unlike some effing dirtbags), and I can prove every part and piece there.  Do your own math, I have roughly $2777 in this rifle (not including tax, almost everything was bought in Central Ohio).  I will answer my calls and texts if there are questions.  I will also answer any questions about the parts or rifle after the deal is done, go to the range with you, or just BS the day away.  Also, Stag has a transferable LIFETIME WARRANTY on all their rifles.  This is absolutely a top-tier Direct Gas AR/M4 and will impress.  I would not have the slightest hesitation taking it to either sandy pit of hell if I ever had to go back.  My name is Gene.  You can call or text at 614-4seven7-8four5three. postcontent: They are indeed forged steel. I have pt1911 and love it, first thing I done was get rid of the crappy cheap ambi safety that falls off after a range trip. Only issues Ive had is ftf while experimenting with other mags. My pt1911 feeds both fmj's and jhp's. I use mine in rotation with other .45's as a defensive carry. I also have a kimber raptor that has been 100% reliable after break in and eats both fmj's and jhp's without any problems using the kimber mags, but doesn't like the chip mccormick mags... I would never sell my pt1911, but probably won't ever buy another one of their products.
